It is noted that because other factors (e.g., beliefs, risk perception, or knowledge related to climate change) have been shown to relate to action on climate change (
 Ohe and Ikeda, 2005; 
 Hidalgo and Pisano, 2010; 
 Vainio and Paloniemi, 2013; 
 Shi et al., 2015; 
 Mase et al., 2016), we tested these factors in conjunction with the variable of the perceived intractability of climate change. We expected that climate change inaction is related to the perceived intractability of climate change, even when controlling for other related variables.
